Wham-Bam Studios A/B Test

Intro

Wham-Bam Studios, a gaming design agency for mobile, ran an A/B test from May 21 to July 31 which aimed at testing whether an experimental feature has a significant impact on Lifetime Value of the user (LTV). Wham-Bam monetises its games by showing ads to users as they play on.

There is a perfect correlation between gamerounds and median number of ads seen. The more gamerounds played, the more time spent playing, the more ad impressions and therefore the more valuable a user.

### read in csv files
assignment <- read_delim("./files/assignment.csv", delim = ",")
activity <- read_delim("./files/activity.csv", delim = ",")
revenue <- read_delim("./files/revenue.csv", delim = ",")
revenues <- read_delim("./files/revenue.csv", delim = ",")


LTV <- activity %>%
  select(logins, gamerounds, ads) %>%
  group_by(logins, gamerounds) %>%
  summarise(ads = median(ads)) %>%
  mutate(logins = as.factor(logins))

LTV_plot <-
  ggplot(data = LTV,
         mapping = aes(x = gamerounds, y = ads, color = logins)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Ads vs. Gamerounds") +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Paired") + theme_classic()

print(LTV_plot)

A total of 5241 users were assigned to the test. 3677 were assigned the control condition and 1564 the experimental condition. Users were assigned over time, the study lasted 77 days in total.

Visualising the data

Examining a plot of daily average gamerounds per group provides an initial intuition of the results of the test. Initially the control group played in average more gamerounds than the test group. As time went on, the difference between the number of gamerounds played by both groups narrowed notoriously. Around mid-June, the test group played consistently more gamerounds than the control group if by a very small difference. Both groups, however, undergo a marked decay in the trend of average daily gamerounds over time. The initial large differences and the subsequent shift to small if steady differences between the number of gamerounds played by each group are interesting phenomena to research more in subsequent exercises. So is the clear decay trend in average daily gamerounds in both groups.

### daily average revenue per impression
### necessary to calculate daily user value and total user value

impresions = c()
revenue_day = c()

for (i in 1:nrow(revenues)) {
  impresions[i] <- activity %>%
    filter(dt == revenues$dt[i]) %>%
    select(ads) %>%
    sum(., na.rm = T)
  
  revenue_day[i] <- revenue %>%
    filter(dt == revenues$dt[i]) %>%
    select(revenue) %>%
    unlist
}

daily_revenue_per_impression <- tibble(dt = revenue$dt,
                                       rev_per_impression = revenue_day /
                                         impresions)

####putting it all together

all_data <-
  activity %>%
  group_by(user_id, dt) %>%
  summarise(
    logins = sum(logins),
    gamerounds = sum(gamerounds),
    ads = sum(ads)
  ) %>%
  left_join(., assignment) %>%
  group_by(dt, casenum) %>%
  summarise(logins = sum(logins),
            gamerounds = sum(gamerounds)) %>%
  mutate(group = factor(casenum)) %>%
  drop_na %>%
  left_join(., daily_revenue_per_impression)

### cumulative sum of assignment for both groups
### necessary to divide daily revenue by the accurate number of users

dt_assignment_control <- assignment %>%
  filter(casenum == 0) %>%
  group_by(assignment_dt) %>%
  summarise(users = n()) %>%
  mutate(total_users = cumsum(users))

dt_assignment_test <- assignment %>%
  filter(casenum == 1) %>%
  group_by(assignment_dt) %>%
  summarise(users = n()) %>%
  mutate(total_users = cumsum(users))

### calculating daily averages of gamerounds per group
### here gamerounds is used as a way into the data exploration

test_data <- all_data %>%
  filter(casenum == 1) %>%
  left_join(., dt_assignment_test, by = c("dt" = "assignment_dt")) %>%
  mutate(gamerounds_per_user = gamerounds / total_users)

control_data <- all_data %>%
  filter(casenum == 0) %>%
  left_join(., dt_assignment_control, by = c("dt" = "assignment_dt")) %>%
  mutate(gamerounds_per_user = gamerounds / total_users)

plot_data <- add_row(
  test_data %>%
    select(dt, gamerounds_per_user) %>%
    mutate(group = "test") %>% ungroup,
  control_data %>%
    select(dt, gamerounds_per_user) %>%
    mutate(group = "control") %>% ungroup
)

a <-

Significance Tests

In order to assess whether there is a significant difference in the LTV of the test and control groups, the following user-level report was built out of the data:

#### putting together all the info so as to have a rich table with all in 
#### to use later for modeling, t-tests and what not

LTV_analysis <- activity %>%
  left_join(., daily_revenue_per_impression) %>%
  left_join(., assignment) %>%
  mutate(daily_rev = ads * rev_per_impression) %>%
  group_by(user_id) %>%
  summarise(
    group = casenum,
    from = min(dt),
    to = max(dt),
    span = if_else(
      to - from == 0,
      as.difftime(1, units = "days"),
      as.difftime(to - from)
    ),
    gamerounds = sum(gamerounds),
    ads = sum(ads),
    total_rev = sum(daily_rev)
  ) %>%
  unique %>%
  mutate(daily_user_rev = total_rev / as.numeric(span)) %>%
  drop_na

kable(head(LTV_analysis), format = "latex", booktabs = TRUE) %>%
  kable_styling(latex_options = "scale_down")

Based on this data, comparisons on different criteria of LTV can be examined: time spent playing, gamerounds played, ads seen and total revenue. For this comparison, outliers (i.e. 1069 users from both groups who played a really high number of gamerounds) were removed to examine both groups more objectively:

par(mar = c(4, 4, .1, .1))

These differences in means are statistically significant. Welch 2 sample T-tests were performed at a 90% confidence interval comparing the span, gamerounds, ads seen and revenue of the test and control groups (without excluding outliers). All of them coincide that the null hypothesis (i.e. there’s no difference between the means of both groups) can be rejected. In other words, 90% of the times in which test and control groups may be sampled and their means and variances compared, the difference lies between the intervals shown below for each variable.

For all variables the test group shows a better performance (i.e. more gamerounds played, more time spent from first to last gameround, more ads seen and more total revenue per user). This is a strong indication that the experimental feature made a positive impact on LTV with the reservations of the relatively low confidence interval (90% as opposed to the 95% industry standard), sampling biases to which the A/B test is subject and the non-normality of the data which may be skewing these significance tests:

Modelling approaches

Fitting a simple regression on the relation between LTV (operationalised now as total revenue per user) and group variable (i.e. control and test conditions) is yet another way to approach the problem:

#### prepare data for xgboost modeling

revenue_y = LTV_analysis$total_rev

LTV_model <- LTV_analysis %>%
  mutate(span = as.numeric(span),
         group = as.numeric(group)) %>% 
  ungroup %>% 
  select(-user_id,-from,-to, -total_rev,-daily_user_rev) %>% 
  as.matrix

#### do a quick lm to explore var relation

LTV_model %>% 
  as_tibble() %>% 
  add_column(revenue_y) %>% 
  lm(revenue_y ~ group, data = .) %>% 
  summary

There is a slight, yet positive relation between the group variable and total revenue per user. This means the test group (coded as 1) has been found to make 0.04 ‘points’ more revenue (the scale of the revenue of users is not clear in the data, hence it’s difficult to quantify properly) than the control group. The significance of this relation in the linear model, however, is only at a 95% confidence level. Further, the model is not very good in terms of the variance it explains (extremely low R squared) given the group condition doesn’t explain much of the variance of revenue per user. Nevertheless, the model coincides with the comparison of means and t-tests in that users from the test group do exhibit higher LTV (expressed in revenue) than the control group.

Yet another modelling approach points to a similar conclusion. The following data was put together for the purposes of fitting a generalised linear model (GLM) using a Poisson distribution and a logarithm link function:

glm_data2 <- glm_data_no_outliers %>% 
  group_by(user_id) %>% 
  summarise(
    logins = sum(logins),
    gamerounds = sum(gamerounds),
    ads = sum(ads),
    group = group,
    time_span = if_else(
      max(dt) - min(dt) == 0,
      as.difftime(1, units = "days"),
      as.difftime(max(dt) - min(dt))
    )
) %>% 
  unique %>% 
  mutate(ad_rate = ads/as.numeric(time_span))

The model shows a very slight yet positive relation between average ads seen and the experimental condition. The difference between these results and the initial mean/median ads visualisations lies on the fact that the GLM fitted using a Poisson distribution takes into consideration the rate of daily ads seen by each user rather than relying on simple group averages:

print_output <- function(output, cex = 0.5) {
  tmp <- capture.output(output)
  plot.new()
  text(0,1, paste(tmp, collapse='\n'), adj = c(0,1), family = 'mono', cex = cex)
  box()
}

ads.glm  = glm(ads ~ factor(group) + gamerounds + logins, family = poisson, offset = log(as.numeric(time_span)), glm_data2)

print_output(summary(ads.glm))

This is therefore a robust alternative result the caveat being, however, the low relative quality of the model indicated by its high AIC. Further, the diagnostic plots show a generally poor model even after having eliminated outliers, which indicates the data is not ideal for fitting a GLM:

par(mar = c(2, 2, .1, .1))
plot(ads.glm)

As a form of conclusion, a deeper analysis into the components of LTV may help Wham-Bam plan future A/B tests. The variables “group” (i.e. test/control), “span” (i.e. length of time between first and last gameround), number of gamerounds played and number of ads seen were modeled against total revenue per user using a boosted trees algorithm (xgboost). The model’s hyper-parameters were tuned using a random search coded as a loop. The model learned the data relatively well, certainly enough for a descriptive analysis of the data (hence no test/validation sets were used). Below a summary of the model as well as some of the predictions of revenue per user and their error:

set.seed(123)

#### functions to fit xgboost

estimate_best_xgboost <- function(xgb_train) {
  watchlist <- list(train = xgb_train)
  best_param = list()
  best_error = Inf
  best_error_index = 0
  set.seed(123)
  
  for (iter in 1:50) {
    param <- list(
      booster = "gbtree",
      objective = "reg:squaredlogerror",
      nthread = 8,
      max_depth = sample(5:10, 1),
      eta = runif(1, .001 ,.55),
      min_child_weight = sample(5:10, 1),
      max_delta_step = sample(0:10, 1),
      interaction_constraints = list(c(1,2,3,4))
    )
    
    mdcv <- xgb.cv(
      data = xgb_train,
      params = param,
      nfold = 3,
      verbose = F,
      early_stopping_rounds = 30,
      maximize = F,
      nrounds = 1000,
      print_every_n = 30,
      watchlist = watchlist,
      seed = 123 
    )
    
    min_error <-
      mdcv$evaluation_log[mdcv$best_iteration]$train_rmsle_mean
    min_error_index <- mdcv$best_iteration
    if (min_error < best_error) {
      best_error <- min_error
      best_error_index <- min_error_index
      best_param <- param
    }
    message(paste(
      "Iteration #",
      iter,
      "error =",
      min_error,
      "min error so far",
      best_error
    ))
  }
  return(best_param)
}

fit_xgboost <- function(train, best_xgb) {
  model <- xgb.train(
    params = best_xgb,
    data = train,
    nrounds = 1000,
    watchlist = list(train = train),
    early_stopping_rounds = 50
  )
  return(model)
}

##### prepare data matrices ---> xgb.Matrix

The analysis of variable importance shows that ads seen is by far the number one determinant of total revenue per user followed by number of gamerounds. Span of time playing and group make a much smaller contribution in comparison. We note that the variable “group” makes the smallest contribution in the explanation of revenue variance. In other words, belonging to the test or control groups doesn’t split the sample in a way in which the delta of revenue would be very significant. This shows that the impact of the A/B test is very limited overall, however it certainly is a step in the right direction.
